---
import OwnerPortrait from "@/components/owner-portrait.astro";
---

<section id="our-story">
  <div class="container mx-auto px-4 py-12 xl:max-w-6xl">
    <h2
      class="text-base-content mb-2 text-xl font-semibold uppercase md:text-3xl"
    >
      Our Story
    </h2>
    <div class="flex flex-col items-start justify-between gap-6 md:flex-row">
      <div class="flex-1">
        <OwnerPortrait />
      </div>
      <div class="flex-1 text-lg">
        <p class="mb-4">
          Bart Swerski didn't set out to open a gastropub. He set out to settle
          an argument.
        </p>
        <p class="mb-4">
          It started, as most good Chicago stories do, over a plate of sausage
          at a Superfans watch party — Bart's cousin Bill hosting, six guys
          named Bill arguing about whether bratwurst or Italian beef was the
          superior tailgate meat. Bart, ever the diplomat, made both. Then he
          made a charcoal-grilled bratwurst with a duck and fig number on the
          side, just to see what would happen.
        </p>
        <p class="mb-4">
          What happened was the argument stopped. Everyone just ate.
        </p>
        <p class="mb-4">
          Twenty years, a culinary degree, and a lot of stubborn recipe testing
          later, Bart opened Wurst & Ale on the corner of Southport and Roscoe —
          a spot he picked mostly because it was a decent walk from Wrigley, and
          Bart firmly believes a good sausage tastes better after a Cubs loss,
          not just a win. The menu grew from there: traditional Bavarian
          classics next to things nobody asked for but everyone orders twice,
          like the rattlesnake sausage that's more legend than gimmick at this
          point.
        </p>
        <p class="mb-4">
          These days, Bart's usually behind the bar himself, pouring a flight,
          arguing about the bullpen, and making sure nobody leaves hungry — or
          without trying something new.
        </p>
        <p class="italic">Da bears may rebuild every year. Da menu doesn't.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
